<Page x:Class="AsynAwaitExamples.Steps.Step02_FirstAsyncAwait"
      xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
      xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
      Title="Step 2 - Your First async/await">
    <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
        <StackPanel Margin="10">
            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource HeaderStyle}" 
                       Text="Step 2: Your First async/await"/>

            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource ExplanationStyle}" xml:space="preserve">THE SOLUTION: Use async/await to do slow work WITHOUT freezing the UI.

Instead of Thread.Sleep (which blocks), we use Task.Delay (which waits WITHOUT blocking).
The "await" keyword says: "Start this operation, give the UI thread back so it can
keep working, and come back here when the operation is done."

Think of it like ordering food at a restaurant: you place your order (start the task),
then you chat with friends (UI stays responsive), and when the food arrives
(task completes), you eat (continue your code).

Click the button and try to move the window - it stays responsive!</TextBlock>

            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="Run ASYNC operation (UI stays responsive!)"
                    Click="RunAsync_Click"/>

            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource ExplanationStyle}" Margin="0,15,0,5"
                       Text="Watch the counter - it keeps running during the async operation:"/>

            <TextBlock x:Name="CounterText" FontSize="24" FontWeight="Bold" 
                       Foreground="#2D6A4F" Margin="0,5,0,10" Text="Counter: 0"/>

            <TextBox x:Name="Output" Style="{StaticResource OutputStyle}" Height="200"/>
        </StackPanel>
    </ScrollViewer>
</Page>
